The superior temporal sulcus (STS) is a deep sulcus of the human brain separating the middle temporal gyrus in the cerebral cortex from the superior temporal gyrus in the insula cortex. The middle temporal gyrus and the superior temporal gyrus are subdivisions of the lateral temporal lobe of the cerebrum. The two gyrus differ largely in structure and function. In primates, typical STS cortical activities include the processing of sight, touch, sound, smell, and learned motion. Hence, the STS has generally been conceived as a multisensory association area and as part of the fusiform face area. A lateral extension of the belt called the posterior temporal sulcus runs from the middle portion of the supramarginal gyrus to a point superiorly at the terminal part of the Wernicke's area. The vergence visual system, serving to help the eyes focus on objects at different distances from the viewer, is predominantly located in the STS. Thus, the STS may likely also contribute to maintaining eye contact during interaction.
